number of tests.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.health.state.mn.us/diseases/coronavirus/situation.html |title=Situation Update for Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19) |access-date=March 16, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200309021508/https://www.health.state.mn.us/diseases/coronavirus/situation.html |archive-date=March 9, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"bringmethenews.com\">{{Cite web |url=https://bringmethenews.com/minnesota-news/minnesotas-confirmed-coronavirus-cases-rise-to-54 |title=Minnesota's confirmed coronavirus cases rise to 54 |access-date=March 16, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317145512/https://bringmethenews.com/minnesota-news/minnesotas-confirmed-coronavirus-cases-rise-to-54 |archive-date=March 17, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Affected counties now include Anoka, [[Benton County, MN|Benton]], [[Blue Earth County, MN|Blue Earth]], Carver, Dakota, Hennepin, [[Olmsted County, MN|Olmsted]], [[Ramsey County, MN|Ramsey]], [[Renville County, MN|Renville]], Stearns, [[Sherburne County, MN|Sherburne]], [[Waseca County, MN|Waseca]], [[Washington County, MN|Washington]], and [[Wright County, MN|Wright]].<ref name=\"bringmethenews.com\" /> Governor Tim Walz has ordered the closure of public places, including all: restaurants, bars, coffee shops, gyms, theaters, breweries, ski resorts, and other public places until at least March 27. Bars and restaurants in the state were closed only to dine in customers; the businesses were allowed to continue to serve customers by take out or delivery orders. He said this order may be extended.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.mprnews.org/story/2020/03/16/walz-covid19-bar-restaurant-closure-and-unemployment-help |title=Walz temporarily closes bars, restaurants and gyms to curb COVID-19 spread |last=MPR Staff |website=Minnesota Public Radio |access-date=17 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317231710/https://www.mprnews.org/story/2020/03/16/walz-covid19-bar-re