-news-20200317-hztvkm3zszfmzj7sgdege2s7z4-story.html?fbclid=IwAR1FQn2A-5JTREXdYX9mmkh__qKlflfrDRGJs1QYKp-1nbuik6viNb1SzDI Coronavirus in Illinois updates: State's 1st death from COVID-19 reported in Chicago] Chicago Tribune, 17 Mar 2020</ref> Turnout for the [[2020 Illinois Democratic primary]] was low, but Chicago broke a World War II-era record for mail-in voting.<ref>[https://www.chicagotribune.com/election-2020/ct-illinois-primary-election-day-updates-20200317-gf5morm2gzbc5j3laniwpr5kx4-story.html Illinois primary updates: Polls about to close after \u2018extremely low\u2019 turnout in Chicago amid coronavirus turmoil] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318032402/https://www.chicagotribune.com/election-2020/ct-illinois-primary-election-day-updates-20200317-gf5morm2gzbc5j3laniwpr5kx4-story.html |date=March 18, 2020 }} Chicago Tribune, 17 Mar 2020</ref>\n*Maryland: Maryland postponed all state primaries until June 2 to reduce the risk of coronavirus infection to the Marylanders.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/03/17/maryland-postpones-april-28-primary-election-over-coronavirus-133776|title=Maryland postpones primary, shifts special election to mail voting over coronavirus|website=POLITICO|language=en|access-date=2020-03-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318104700/https://www.politico.com/news/2020/03/17/maryland-postpones-april-28-primary-election-over-coronavirus-133776|archive-date=March 18, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*Minnesota: The Minnesota Department of Health announced that due to the national shortage of materials for medical testing for the virus they will be limiting testing to those who are hospitalized, ill healthcare workers and those who live in long-term care facilities. The restrictions will be in place until the state is supplied with additional tests.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fox9.com/news/minnesota-dept-of-health-narrowing-testing-criteria-amid-national-shortage-of-covid-19-tests|title=Minnesota Dept. of Health narrowing testing criteria amid national shortage of COVID-19 tests|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n*North Carolina: The state announced that it had 65 confirmed coronavirus cases.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.newsobserver.com/news/coronavirus/article241238276.html |title=Coronavirus live updates: Here's what to know in North Carolina on March 17 |last=Simone |first=Jasper |date=17 March 2020 |website=The News & Observer |url-status=live |access-date=17 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317163612/https://www.newsobserver.com/news/coronavirus/article241238276.html |archive-date=March 17, 2020 }}</ref> The state also announced that it had run 1,100 tests.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Murphy |first=Brian |url=https://www.newsobserver.com/news/coronavirus/article241270931.html |title=More than 1,100 coronavirus tests have been run, and NC is prepping for more |date=17 March 2020 |work=The News & Observer |url-status=live |access-date=March 18, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318174607/https://www.newsobserver.com/news/coronavirus/article241270931.html |archive-date=March 18, 2020 }}</ref>\n* Ohio: The state had 67 confirmed cases.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://abc6onyourside.com/news/local/march-17-coronavirus-in-ohio-update|title=67 confirmed coronavirus cases in Ohio, 17 people hospitalized|first=Lu Ann|last=Stoia|date=March 17, 2010|website=abc6onyourside.com|access-date=March 18, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317200446/https://abc6onyourside.com/news/local/march-17-coronavirus-in-ohio-update|archive-date=March 17, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Governor DeWine orders that elective surgeries be postponed.<ref name= \"CBS10 TIMELINE\"/>\n*Pennsylvania: All liquor stores closed indefinitely.<ref>[https://edition.cnn.com/world/live-news/coronavirus-outbreak-03-16-20-intl-hnk/h_6e1f01640b115ad8c8c625f496fd06a5?fbclid=IwAR34M94sJN_64OBSI90MNjOkjhlJMxMX6c69pUluy-BwjnGaOr_fO1Vgx6A Pennsylvania closes all state liquor stores indefinitely] By Ben Westcott, Helen Regan, Adam Renton, Meg Wagner and Veronica Rocha, CNN, March 17, 2020</ref>\n*South Carolina: Governor McMaster issues an executive order requiring the mandatory shutdown of dine-in service in restaurants and bars and prevented a gathering of more than 50 people. The state also had 47 cases.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wfae.org/post/sc-governor-places-restrictions-bars-and-restaurants-slow-coronavirus-spread|title=SC Governor Places Restrictions On Bars And Restaurants To Slow Coronavirus Spread|last=Delia|first=Sarah|website=wfae.org|language=en|access-date=2020-03-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318140534/https://www.wfae.org/post/sc-governor-places-restrictions-bars-and-restaurants-slow-coronavirus-spread|archive-date=March 18, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Oregon: The governor extended school closures through April 28.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.koin.com/news/health/governor-brown-extends-school-closure-to-april-28/|title=Oregon governor extends school closure through April 28|website=koin.com|access-date=2020-03-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320205626/https://www.koin.com/news/health/governor-brown-extends-school-closure-to-april-28/|archive-date=March 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*South Dakota: Closure of K-12 schools extended an extra week. Set to resume on March, 30.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.keloland.com/news/healthbeat/coronavirus/gov-noem-gives-covid-19-update-in-sioux-falls-tuesday/ |title=Gov. Noem: South Dakota schools to remain closed for another week |date=2020-03-17 |website=KELOLAND.com |language=en-US |access-date=2020-03-17 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318081507/https://www.keloland.com/news/healthbeat/coronavirus/gov-noem-gives-covid-19-update-in-sioux-falls-tuesday/ |archive-date=March 18, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n*Texas: The second death in Texas has been reported. A resident of a retirement community in Arlington died on Sunday, March 15.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcdfw.com/news/coronavirus/arlington-resident-dies-from-coronavirus-first-in-north-texas/2333046/|title=Arlington Resident Dies From Coronavirus, First in North Texas|accessdate=Mar 19, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319042244/https://www.nbcdfw.com/news/coronavirus/arlington-resident-dies-from-coronavirus-first-in-north-texas/2333046/|archive-date=March 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*Virginia: Governor Northam announced a ban of gatherings of more than 10 people. 15 new cases are reported, bringing the total to 67 cases in Virginia.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.wsls.com/news/virginia/2020/03/17/15-new-coronavirus-cases-in-virginia-now-67-total-cases/ |title=15 new coronavirus cases in Virginia, now 67 total cases |last=Williamson |first=Jeff |date=2020-03-17 |website=WSLS |language=en |access-date=2020-03-18 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318041135/https://www.wsls.com/news/virginia/2020/03/17/15-new-coronavirus-cases-in-virginia-now-67-total-cases/ |archive-date=March 18, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> \n*[[West Virginia]]: Confirmed its first case; it was the last US state to do so.<ref name=\"Mar17_WV\">{{Cite news |url=https://myfox8.com/news/coronavirus/west-virginia-the-last-us-state-without-coronavirus-confirms-1st-case/ |title=West Virginia, the last US state without coronavirus, confirms 1st case |access-date=March 17, 2020 |agency=Associated Press |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317224314/https://myfox8.com/news/coronavirus/west-virginia-the-last-us-state-without-coronavirus-confirms-1st-case/ |archive-date=March 17, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==== March 18 ====\n* Florida: U.S. congressman [[Mario D\u00edaz-Balart]] is one of the first members of Congress to be tested positive for coronavirus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/18/politics/mario-diaz-balart-coronavirus/index.html|title=Reps. Mario Diaz-Balart and Ben McAdams become first members of Congress to test positive for coronavirus|first=Paul|last=Leblanc|date=March 18, 2020|website=cnn.com|access-date=March 21, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321105409/https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/18/politics/mario-diaz-balart-coronavirus/index.html|archive-date=March 21, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Thousands of spring-breakers flock to Florida beaches despite warnings about keeping social distance. The [[Clearwater, Florida|Clearwater City Council]] voted to close down [[Clearwater Beach]] for two weeks, starting March 23 at 6 a.m. The coronavirus has infected 328 Florida residents and visitors.<ref>[https://news.yahoo.com/thousands-flock-florida-beaches-ignoring-060744453.html Thousands flock to Florida beaches, ignoring coronavirus concerns] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320221138/https://news.yahoo.com/thousands-flock-florida-beaches-ignoring-060744453.html |date=March 20, 2020 }} by Sophie Lewis, CBS New, 18 Mar 2020</ref>\n*Kentucky: The wife of [[List of mayors of Louisville, Kentucky|Louisville mayor]] [[Greg Fischer]] tested positive for coronavirus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.courier-journal.com/story/news/politics/metro-government/2020/03/18/louisville-mayor-greg-fischers-wife-tests-positive-covid-19/2869369001/|title=Louisville Mayor Greg Fischer's wife tests positive for coronavirus, will self-isolate|first=Darcy|last=Costello|website=The Courier-Journal|accessdate=Mar 19, 2020}}</ref>\n*Louisiana: Rev. Tony Spell of Life Tabernacle Church in [[East Baton Rouge Parish]] hosts hundreds at a church service in open defiance of Governor [[John Bel Edwards|John Bel Edwards']] (D) ban against gatherings of more than 50 people.<ref>[https://thehill.com/policy/healthcare/488318-louisiana-church-defies-coronavirus-recommendations-to-hold-service-for-300?fbclid=IwAR3Fy0WDhtRR-_dCFyYFj1nXwqMw1aeImfznyKF5NlxAGjGEZSsIeQjcYXo Louisiana church defies coronavirus recommendations to hold service for 300] BY ZACK BUDRYK, The Hill, 18 Mar 2020</ref>\n* Maryland: The state added 22 more coronavirus cases, to the total of 63 cases.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/maryland-virginia-dc-coronavirus-tuesday-updates/2020/03/17/5f6fa73c-684e-11ea-9923-57073adce27c_story.html|title=Coronavirus cases surge as Northam bans gatherings of more than 10, Hogan postpones primary|last=Chason|first=Rachel|date=18 March 2020|website=Washington Post|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318121502/https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/maryland-virginia-dc-coronavirus-tuesday-updates/2020/03/17/5f6fa73c-684e-11ea-9923-57073adce27c_story.html|archive-date=March 18, 2020|access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n*Michigan: The first death from coronavirus in the state is reported, a man in his 50s who had underlying medical conditions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.clickondetroit.com/news/local/2020/03/18/man-at-wayne-county-hospital-is-michigans-first-confirmed-coronavirus-death/|title=Man at Wayne County hospital is Michigan's first confirmed coronavirus death|website=clickondetroit.com|accessdate=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318231056/https://www.clickondetroit.com/news/local/2020/03/18/man-at-wayne-county-hospital-is-michigans-first-confirmed-coronavirus-death/|archive-date=March 18, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The state also announces 30 more confirmed cases, bringing the total number there to 110.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.clickondetroit.com/news/local/2020/03/18/michigan-officials-state-has-at-least-30-more-confirmed-cases-of-coronavirus-covid-19-bringing-total-to-110/|title=Michigan officials: State has at least 30 more confirmed cases of coronavirus (COVID-19), bringing total to 110|website=clickondetroit.com|accessdate=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318231055/https://www.clickondetroit.com/news/local/2020/03/18/michigan-officials-state-has-at-least-30-more-confirm