onavirus-cases-continues-testing-2020-mar|title=88 confirmed cases of coronavirus in Ohio; 26 hospitalized|date=March 18, 2020|website=10tv.com|access-date=March 18, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318055740/https://www.10tv.com/article/ohio-confirms-first-coronavirus-cases-continues-testing-2020-mar|archive-date=March 18, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Governor Mike DeWine announces that 181 BMV locations will close until further notice. Five will stay open to process commercial driver license applications and renewal. DeWine asked the state legislature to pass a grace period for people whose licenses expired. Barbershops, salons, and tattoo parlors closed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbc4i.com/community/health/coronavirus/coronavirus-in-ohio-wednesday-update-from-governor-odh-set-for-for-2-p-m/|title=Coronavirus in Ohio Wednesday update: 88 cases of COVID-19 confirmed|date=March 18, 2020|website=nbc4i.com|access-date=March 18, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318211617/https://www.nbc4i.com/community/health/coronavirus/coronavirus-in-ohio-wednesday-update-from-governor-odh-set-for-for-2-p-m/|archive-date=March 18, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Businesses that do stay open are being asked to take their employees' temperatures every day before they come to work and send sick employees home.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbc4i.com/community/health/coronavirus/dewine-businesses-should-take-employees-temperatures-every-day/|title=DeWine: Businesses should take temperatures of employees every day|date=March 18, 2020|website=nbc4i.com|access-date=March 18, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318211624/https://www.nbc4i.com/community/health/coronavirus/dewine-businesses-should-take-employees-temperatures-every-day/|archive-date=March 18, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Mayor Andrew Ginther declared a state of emergency in [[Columbus, Ohio]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbc4i.com/community/health/coronavirus/mayor-ginther-d